description.plain: Rita Ora is an Albanian-British singer/songwriter and actress who rose to prominence with her 2012 debut album ORA. Since then she has maintained her appearances on the pop charts and has also branched out into other ventures like acting and fashion endorsements. After a long legal dispute with her previous label Roc Nation, her second album Phoenix  was released through Atlantic Records UK in 2018. It charted internationally in over twenty countries and peaked at #11 in the UK.

description.plain:
“Girls” is the third official single from Rita Ora’s upcoming album. The song tackles themes of female empowerment, self-love, and bisexuality.

The song was met with backlash initiated by lesbian icon Hayley Kiyoko – it was accused of being “tone-deaf” and “fueling the male gaze”. Ora has since issued an apology via Twitter.

Initially, Rita debuted a version of the song live at the BBC Radio 1’s Big Weekend on May 28, 2017 with fellow British artists, RAYE and Charli XCX. The three previously collaborated on the VIP mix of Charli’s “After the Afterparty.”

In a November interview with The Big Top 40, Rita confirmed Bebe Rexha and Charli XCX as collaborators on the track. Bebe then teased a third featured artist. In December, this was leaked by ThatGrapeJuice to be Cardi B, which was later confirmed by Rita herself as she unveiled the release date along with an alternate promotional cover art for the song two days prior to the song’s release.

description.plain:
“Anywhere” is the second single off of her second album Phoenix. According to Ora herself, “Anywhere” is a love song. Rita explained more about the song by saying:

“Anywhere” is super important with everything going on, The core of this song was written in L.A., and I really wanted to get out of there. I felt too still and that every day was the same for me, so I wrote a song called “Anywhere” basically saying, ‘Take me anywhere, anywhere away from here.’ We turned that into ‘Anywhere away with you,’ and it became this incredible love song."

“Anywhere” was written by Alesso, Ali Tamposi, Andrew Wotman, Brian Lee, Sir Nolan, and Ora.

description.plain:
In an intimate and confessional manner, electro-pop song “Let You Love Me”, by
British singer Rita Ora talks about regret and reflection when it comes to difficulties and mistakes made by someone in the romance area of life.

Very much a twenty-first-century song, in terms of the more equal roles men and
women can play, in all aspects of life, the lyrics explore that a female can have, very well, exactly the same issues men always had, when it comes to fears of commitment and intimacy.

description.plain:
Following the success of “Poison” in the UK, Rita looks to make her mark Stateside with her first single in the USA off her upcoming sophomore album. “Body On Me” features a man accustomed to chart success in Chris Brown as the pair get intimate on the record.

Chris may seem an odd choice as a feature considering his history with Rita’s Roc Nation label mate Rihanna, but in an interview, she defended him saying:

I love him on different levels. I see how he treats his people and he’s a good person with a good heart and a lovely family. It’s really nice that we finally got together because, regardless of what’s happened, the song is just amazing.

“Goldfinger” was intended to appear on Rita Ora’s second album, Phoenix (2018). The song features rapper 2 Chainz. Ora had spoken about the song in several interviews and it had appeared on an album track list accidentally posted by Warner in September 2018, but had been removed when the final track list was announced later in October.  The song has since leaked online.

Ora wrote the song with Ali Tamposi, Brian Lee, and Andrew Watt, with an added verse by 2 Chainz and production from Felix Snow.

According to the June 2017 issue (76) of Notion magazine: ￼

“Goldfinger” is a sexy slow jam that hints at the female version of “Shape of You￼”.  It was inspired by Ernő Goldfinger, the architect behind Trellick Tower.￼

Rita said of 2 Chainz in an interview with Z100’s Shelley Rome (June 2017):

I love him. It’s like the best friendship ever. He’s the coolest cat in the world. People are so surprised, but me and him are like actually friends. He’s like my homey. I love him so much. He knows so much and I guess he’s lived through a lot, so like, you know, he’s one of my favorite rappers in the world, so I’m happy that we got to do something finally￼.

“Goldfinger” is a sexy slow jam that hints at the female version of “Shape of You￼”.  It was inspired by Ernő Goldfinger, the architect behind Trellick Tower.￼

Rita said of 2 Chainz in an interview with Z100’s Shelley Rome (June 2017):

I love him. It’s like the best friendship ever. He’s the coolest cat in the world. People are so surprised, but me and him are like actually friends. He’s like my homey. I love him so much. He knows so much and I guess he’s lived through a lot, so like, you know, he’s one of my favorite rappers in the world, so I’m happy that we got to do something finally￼.

description.plain:
The original version of Iggy’s second The New Classic single “Bounce”. This version of the song would only feature Iggy with Rita Ora being credited as the lead. On August 2021 while promoting her third studio album The End of An Era Iggy Azalea sat down for an interview at the Zach Sang Show where among other things she discussed the origins of the song and her dislike of it.
She revealed that her record company sent her the song, intended for Rita at the time, as a reference with her only adding her verses to it. In the Spring of 2013 and as she was about to start filming for her eight-week-long campaign of VEVO LIFT she was asked to submit songs for consideration. She had only started working at her debut studio album, so this “unfinished” version was one of the songs she was forced to send.
When the producers and her company liked it, they asked her to keep working on it as a solo track, eventually removing Rita, adding more verses etc. The reworked final version ended up being included on The New Classic only as a bonus track.
